Following our  7 day power monitoring and site inspection I have the following to report:

During the period 12/4-18/4, we observed average current in the Orbit Tenancy was between 40-50A, however on 14th and on 18th April the maximum current peaked around 95Amps per phase

The building consumer mains was measured on 18-20th April with the peaks ranging between 125A and 145A. The cable being 70mm 4C+E XLPE which protected by 125-160A service protective device (SPD trip settings unknown) is at its limit.  As such he overall building load should be considered and not be increased with out further investigation.

The Orbit sub-mains consist of 10mm 4C+E O/C which is installed in underground conduit. This is rated to 63A and is protected by a 63A 3 phase breaker.  The sub-main breaker is tripping occasionally due to over-current which is not acceptable consistant electrical overload presents a fire risk.

Recommendations:
Option A

To remedy this situation would require upgrading the building, main switchboard to CT metering (over 100A, and upgrade the sub-mains to the Orbit tenancy.  This would allow for an increase in supply to meet your needs. Ideally Orbit tenancy is suited to a 150A supply via CT metering and upgraded sub-mains.
Cost Estimate is somewhere between $50-70k. 

Option B
An interim fix is to get additional power from the lawyers tenancy next door which you occupy part of. This would involve:

1. Upgrade the tenancy sub-mains and circuit protection. Approx $2,800
2. Upgrade the lawyers main switchboard to accomodate additional power load, approx $1,800
3. Install a second sub-main to Orbit tenancy with a new sub-board fed from the lawyers supply, approx $2,000
4. Rewire 2 existing machines to the new sub-board. approx $1,900
Approx total for option B would be $8500 +gst

This is only an estimate. We can provide a fixed quote on your direction to go ahead. 

Notes
-Orbit DB currently tripping at high load. Check for faults and calculate loads for current equipment and future needs.
-Complete site inspection and return trip to install 3-Phase Power Quality & Energy Analyser power monitoring to Orbit dry cleaning and return trip to transfer power monitoring to building mains.
-This information is necessary to work out how to best distribute the increased load between Orbit tenancy and 2nd power supply from solicitors distribution board.
-Labour cost include initial site visit and three return trips to install Analyser to Orbit, transfer to mains and remove.

ELECTRICAL SERVICES
1. EXISTING FLOOR DISTRIBUTION BOARD TO REMAIN, PROVIDE ADDITIONAL SWITCHGEAR TO NEW CIRCUITS AS SHOWN IN THE POWER LAYOUT.
2. CIRCUIT BREAKERS TO MATCH THE EXISTING.
3. ALL CIRCUIT BREAKERS MINIMUM FAULT CURRENT CAPACITY TO MATCH THE EXISTING BOARD.
4. ALL CIRCUIT BREAKERS SELECTED SHALL TO PROVIDE FULL DISCRIMINATION BETWEEN ALL UPSTREAM AND DOWNSTREAM PROTECTION DEVICES. CONTRACTOR TO UNDERTAKE A DISCRIMINATION STUDY AND OBTAIN PROTECTION SETTINGS FROM THE SUPPLY AUTHORITY WHERE REQUIRED, TO ENSURE SERVICE
PROTECTION DEVICES GRADE WITH THE SUPPLY AUTHORITIES PROTECTION DEVICES.
5. ALL RESIDUAL CURRENT DEVICES SHALL BE OF THE SAME MANUFACTURER TO MATCH THE EXISTING TYPE.
6. EXISTING POWER AND LIGHTING CIRCUITS TO BE DISCONNECTED AND REMOVED, UNLESS STATED OTHERWISE. REFER LIGHTING AND POWER LAYOUT.
7. ANY RE-USE OF FINAL SUB-CIRCUIT CABLING SHALL BE ACCOMPANIED BY A TEST WITH THE RESULTS RECORDED AND SUBMITTED.
8. SUPPLY AND INSTALL NEW WIRING TO ALL NEW LIGHTING AND POWER CIRCUITS UNLESS STATED OTHERWISE. REFER LIGHTING AND POWER LAYOUT.
9. SUPPLY AND INSTALL NEW RCD PROTECTION FOR GENERAL POWER CIRCUITS IN ACCORDANCE WITH AS/NZS 3000.
10. PROVIDE NEW / UPDATED CIRCUIT SCHEDULE FOR DISTRIBUTION BOARD AND TAG ALL THE CIRCUITS.
LIGHTING
1. SUPPLY, INSTALL AND CONNECT ALL NEW LIGHTING LUMINAIRES AS INDICATED INCLUDING ALL FIXINGS, BRACKETS ETC AS REQUIRED.
2. PROVIDE RCD PROTECTION TO ALL LIGHTING CIRCUITS IN ACCORDANCE WITH AS/NZS 3000.
3. PROVIDE NEW LIGHT SWITCHES IN THE AREAS INDICATED.
4. ALL LIGHT SWITCHES SHALL BE FITTED WITH DURABLE IDENTIFICATION LABELS DISPLAYING DISTRIBUTION BOARD AND CIRCUIT BREAKER NUMBERS.
5. SHOULD THE CONTRACTOR SUBMIT ALTERNATIVE LUMINAIRES FOR CONSIDERATION THEN THE FOLLOWING REQUIREMENTS WITH SUPPORTING DOCUMENTATION SHALL BE PROVIDED. ALTERNATIVES SHALL NOT BE CONSIDERED IF THIS INFORMATION IS NOT PROVIDED. THE INFORMATION PROVIDED SHALL BE
SUPPLIED TO THE CONSULTANT FREE OF CHARGE AND AT NO COST TO THE CONSULTANT. THE CONSTRUCTION PROGRAM SHALL ALLOW A MINIMUM OF 4 BUSINESS DAYS FOR THE CONSULTANT TO REVIEW THE COMPLETE SET OF DOCUMENTS FOR THE ALTERNATIVE LUMINAIRES SUBMITTED.
5.1.ALTERNATIVE LUMINAIRES SHALL USE LED CHIPS FROM REPUTABLE MANUFACTURERS WITH PROVEN EXPERIENCE IN LED PRODUCTION, SUCH AS CREE, OSRAM, NICHEA, XICATO AND LUXEON.
5.2.LUMINAIRES SHALL USE HIGH EFFICIENCY LED CHIPS, WITH A MINIMUM EFFICACY OF 80LM/W.
5.3.LUMINAIRES DESIGNED TO COMPLY WITH THE LED CHIP MANUFACTURERS SPECIFICATIONS INCLUDING THE MINIMUM THERMAL REQUIREMENTS.
5.4.USE LED CHIPS THAT ARE WITHIN 3 SDCM (STANDARD DEVIATION COLOUR MATCHING) MACADAM STEPS FOR INTERNAL LUMINAIRES AND WITHIN 4 SDCM STEPS FOR EXTERNAL LUMINAIRES.
5.5.USE LED BOARDS IN THE FITTING THAT ARE REPLACEABLE, TO AVOID THE NEED TO DISPOSE OF THE WHOLE FITTING IN THE EVENT OF LED FAILURE.
5.6.MINIMUM EXPECTED LIFE OF LED CHIPS AT L70 OF 50,000 HOURS.
5.7.PROVIDE NATA CERTIFIED (OR EQUIVALENT) PHOTOMETRIC TESTING.
5.8.CERTIFIED TO AUSTRALIAN STANDARDS AND REGULATORS (OR HIGHER) AND CARRY THE AUSTRALIAN REGULATORY COMPLIANCE MARK (RCM).
5.9.DATASHEETS OF THE PROPOSED ALTERNATIVES, WHICH SHOULD INCLUDE AS A MINIMUM, WATTAGE, EXIT LUMENS, COLOUR TEMPERATURE, AND COLOUR RENDERING INDEX.
5.10. A COPY OF LM-80 RESULTS FOR EACH ALTERNATIVE LUMINAIRE.
5.11. A COPY OF TM-21 REPORT FOR EACH ALTERNATIVE LUMINAIRE.
5.12. A COPY OF LM-79 REPORT FOR EACH ALTERNATIVE LUMINAIRE.
5.13. PROVIDE A WARRANTY STATEMENT FOR EACH ALTERNATIVE LUMINAIRE.
5.14. PROVIDED ILLUMINATION SIMULATIONS, AGI32 OR DIALUX LIGHTING ILLUMINATION CALCULATIONS DETAILING THE ILLUMINATION LEVELS. THE CALCULATIONS SHALL DETAIL MAINTENANCE FACTOR USED, WORKING PLANE HEIGHTS OF CALCULATION POINTS, AND LIGHTING PARAMETERS IN ACCORDANCE WITH AS1680
(SUCH AS AVERAGE ILLUMINANCE AND UNIFORMITY AS A MINIMUM).
5.15. A COST COMPARISON DETAILING THE PROPOSED CREDIT BEING OFFERED FOR EACH LUMINAIRE TYPE.
5.16. A DETAILED REPORT FOR THE LIGHT POWER DENSITIES FOR EACH AREA TO CONFIRM LIGHT POWER DENSITY (LPD IN W/m2) IN ACCORDANCE WITH NCC/BCA REQUIREMENTS.

- Supply and install external DB box as per TA-STD-761.

- Relocate existing GPOs within shelter as requested by HighForce technician.
- Relocate existing AC DB and SPD box to a temporary location to make room to relocate QPF rack.
- Recover existing A/C unit. Close the wall penetration.

-2nd Mobilisation (MOB2)

- 3rd Mobilisation (MOB3)
- Decommission and remove the old NSWPF submains from GMP. 
- Remove old AC DB and SPD box from shelter.

Energy Renewal Tender:
TPS is seeking to form a select panel of 5 suppliers from the Prequalification Scheme for General Construction Works Valued up to $1 million (SCM0256) to renew the existing Stand-Alone Power Systems (SAPS) in the Royal National Park (Wattamolla and Garie Visitor Precincts). 
Tender and delivery indicative timeframe – mandatory Tender Briefing will be held on site in late January 2025 (details confirmed within tender invite) with the proposed contracted works to be completed by no later 30 June 2025.

 

The renewal of the of the existing SAPS for the Wattamolla and Garie Visitor Precincts as a result of the increasing maintenance costs, increased fuel costs due to longer running times of the backup diesel generators due to battery decay and overall higher system demand resulting from rising visitation.

 

The contract will be completed in a two staged approach

Stage 1 DESIGN – lump sum to complete detailed inspection & investigation including design of each SAPS renewal needs
Stage 2 INSTALLATION – based on the renewal needs from Stage 1 a schedule of rates will be used to facilitate the works
 

The scope of works is the same for both locations (not limited to)

Each location has a Stand-Alone Power System (SAPS) – solar panels, inverters, battery back-up and supported by a diesel generator when the level of the batteries drop.
Some of the equipment is reaching the end of their life (Garie installed in 2009 Wattamolla in 2017).
Each company will need to test existing systems and determine the life cycle of each element and if they need to be replaced / upgrade.
NPWS want the capacity increased to cater for future needs.
Several background reports have been undertaken, which will be provided to the tenderers.
Tenderers will be required to design and install the upgrade SAPS.
Works will be completed under an MW21 Contract.
 

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to call me.

Proposed Timeline (Rough Estimate from Darren):

October – Master bedroom side of the house: general lights and power

November – Kitchen end of the house: general lights and power

January 2026 – Top paddock: guesthouse/shed

Obviously these dates are rough at this stage, but they give us a working framework.

Planning Discussion

I think it’s important we schedule a proper sit-down with Darren and his wife—ideally with a floor plan (even a basic sketch) to go over everything thoroughly:

What they want installed or upgraded

What existing infrastructure is staying or being removed (e.g., A/C)

What we can lock in, knowing some details will likely evolve

This would give us a solid foundation and help eliminate confusion later on.

Rewire Opportunity

I haven’t brought this up with Darren yet, but a full rewire of the house is worth considering. The current roof space wiring is well below standard—completely non-compliant. Given he wants to remove the kitchen ceiling and convert it to a vaulted ceiling (where much of the dodgy wiring is), it's the perfect time to address this properly.

Solar/Battery/Genset System

There seems to be a bit of a disconnect between Darren’s understanding of the system and what’s actually in place—high chance the confusion stems from me!

Regardless, I think it would be valuable for Josh to spend whatever time is needed onsite to map out the entire system and identify what’s done vs. what’s still required.

We should also aim to compile full handover documentation for the system, including:

Wiring diagrams

Warranties

Service schedules/recommendations (potential opportunity for us)

Step-by-step user guides

A flowchart showing how the system behaves under different conditions (e.g., backup sequences)

If the system isn’t currently 100% automatic, we’ll need to scope and quote for an ATS (Automatic Transfer Switch) and make a call on that with Darren.

Also, he’s keen for the backup system to eventually support the guesthouse/shed in the top paddock. We’ll need to assess if the current setup can handle that or if upgrades are necessary.

As you mentioned, Dale—there might be a great opportunity here to propose a completely off-grid solution for that part of the property.
